description.value: Gypsum alabaster (calcium sulphate) bowl.  Fragment. Only about one third of the shallow basin is preserved, two of the three supporting figures are missing; the preserved siren is missing the head and the figure in her arms is lacking head and upper body. The upper part of the left wing has been replaced by a piece from the edge of the bowl. There are possible traces of smoke residue visible. The missing parts were replaced by a modern plaster cast.  The shallow basin has a flat lip, around the edge of which a plastically rendered tongue pattern (Eierstab) is running. Three figures were holding up the basin originally, of which one remains in the form of a Siren with long curving wings, carrying a child at her breast. The widely spread wings are supporting the bottom of the basin. The head is missing; long tresses fall on the shoulders.  The upper part is female with a sleeved garment visible; the lower part is scaled while ending in a bird's tail. On the left side, the body ends in the egg-like form; on the right side, the tail is shown in relief above the feathers. The human figure held by the siren like a child is wearing a long chiton; the legs are angled and the arms were held up towards the siren's upper body.

The interior of the rim is decorated with groups of five short strokes.
